\begin_layout Section
Encryption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Windows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
GNU/Linux
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
GNU/Linux distributions include many tools to encrypt whole directories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
With Paperwork, there are 2 directories that should be encrypted to protect
 your privacy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Your work directory (by default ~/papers, can be changed in the settings)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cache directory (~/.local/share/paperwork, cannot be changed) (it contains
 index files from which the content of your documents could be partially
 recovered)
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Will be changed to ~/.cache/paperwork
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ecryptfs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
On GNU/Linux Debian and Ubuntu, you can easily create a directory Private
 in your home directory.
 This directory will be encrypted using the password you use to connect
 when you start your computer.
 Just type ecryptfs-setup-private in a terminal to create it.
 You have to logout/login agan.
 You can then put the work directory of Paperwork in it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Once the directory has been created, you can also store Paperwork cache
 in it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
$ mv ~/.local/share/paperwork ~/Private/paperwork_cache
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
$ ln -s ~/Private/paperwork_cache ~/.local/share/paperwork
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Encfs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Encfs can also be used to create encrypted directories easily.
 However, Encfs seems to have some security weaknesses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
$ enfs ~/.papers ~/papers
\end_layout

